        <comment>
  <id>102344552</id>
  <body><![CDATA[Hi Florence,<br /><br />The plot thickens. I have read that Harper Lee does suffer at this point with dementia. Later in the day, yesterday, after I posted that correction, I read another piece where her sister Alice---who practiced law until she was 100---stated that Harper Lee DID sign permission for the book but doesn't remember it now. This would be consistent with the uproar that arose in the last couple of years where Harper Lee also signed away the control of the To Kill A Mockingbird copyright to the son of her longtime (now deceased) literary agent. Then she sued him to regain control of the copyright based on the premise that she suffered from dementia and did not know what she was signing.<br /><br />Sad all around.<br /><br />Apparently her older sister Alice is much more lucid, even to this day. Based upon everything I've read since my last post in this thread, I'm inclined to deduce that Nelle Harper Lee probably agreed to participate in this upcoming book but has no memory of it. Alice states that her sister may not have understood the 2011 agreement she signed for this new book, since she suffered a stroke in 2007:<br /><br />"Poor Nelle Harper can't see and can't hear and will sign anything put before her by anyone in whom she has confidence. Now she has no memory of the incident, " Alice Lee wrote. <br /><br /><a target="_blank" href="http://www.people.com/article/harper-lee-claims-marja-mills-memoir-unauthorized" rel="nofollow">http://www.people.com/article/harper-...</a><br /><br />And here is a fascinating piece about Alice Lee (a remarkable woman in her own right):<br /><br /><a target="_blank" href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/04/01/harper-lee-s-sister-alice-is-100-still-practices-law-and-remembers-everything.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles...</a><br /><br />________<br /><br />RT]]></body>
  
