        <comment>
  <id>102381193</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>Florence (Lefty) wrote: "Just so you know have been eyeballing your group for a while, so tempting - and Mockingbird: A Portrait of Harper Lee looks great, thanks for that. Her connection with Capote also fascinates me (I'm a fan of both of them) which I'm sure is covered in this book."</i><br /><br />I've always been intrigued with Ms. Lee's and Capote's relationship. It is covered well in "Mockingbird" and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/926177.Capote_A_Biography" title="Capote A Biography by Gerald Clarke" rel="nofollow">Capote: A Biography</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/38368.Gerald_Clarke" title="Gerald Clarke" rel="nofollow">Gerald Clarke</a>. Although I found George Plimpton's bio entertaining. I recommend the Clarke.<br /><br />Amasa Lee gave an old typewriter to his daughter and Capote. They spent many hours composing stories in their childhood when Capote would be visiting his relatives the Faulks in Monroeville.<br /><br />Harper Lee was instrumental in being the point person in gaining Capote interviews for <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/168642.In_Cold_Blood" title="In Cold Blood by Truman Capote" rel="nofollow">In Cold Blood</a>. While writing what he considered his masterpiece, Harper Lee was awarded the Pulitzer Prize. Capote resented it. That he never won the Pulitzer was a factor that was always a burr under his saddle.<br /><br />The friendship between the two childhood friends began to unravel as a result of Capote's jealousy. He gave Lee no credit for her voluminous notes on interviews. He did not invite her to his famous "White Ball" after she won the Pulitzer. And, most petty, Capote began the rumor that he was the true author of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2657.To_Kill_a_Mockingbird" title="To Kill a Mockingbird by Harper Lee" rel="nofollow">To Kill a Mockingbird</a>.<br /><br />Interestingly, long before Lee inserted Capote into her novel as Dill, Capote created a brash tomboyish character in his first novel <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2287.Other_Voices__Other_Rooms" title="Other Voices, Other Rooms by Truman Capote" rel="nofollow">Other Voices, Other Rooms</a> in 1948. The brash, immodest tomboy sounds as though she might be a more mature Scout.]]></body>
  
